Cleaning

The first issue about the dataset that needs correction is the format of how the sequence counts of an individual sequence_id are stored in the dataset. Each sequence is stored vertically and the sequence counts for each sequence_id are not necessarily the same.

The difference in sequence counter lengths is due to the difference in times in how long each gesture might take to complete. The different sequence counter lengths require standardization as part of the process of cleaning the dataset. (I wonder if it is feature engineering or data cleaning. It has to be complete before any other data cleaning or feature engineering is complete).

def interpolate_raw(df, n_f=number_of_timesteps):
    # The original function expects a single Series, so we'll adjust it.
    # The interpolation logic will be applied to each row (axis=1).
    s_o_local = df.dropna()
    n_o = s_o_local.shape[0]
    print(df)
    # Guard against empty or single-point series after dropna
    if n_o < 2:
        return np.full(n_f, np.nan)
        
    t_o = np.linspace(0, n_o, n_o)
    t_f = np.linspace(0, n_o, n_f)
        
    s_f = np.interp(t_f, t_o, s_o_local.values)
    print(s_f)
    return s_f

(cleaning) Only the IMU data is used from the dataset. For the purposes of the assignment, a limited dataset should suffice.

In [12]:
features_raw = defaultdict(list)

features = defaultdict(list)

for feature in feature_names:
    for name, group in modified_df.groupby('sequence_id'):
        if feature == 'columns':
            tmp = pd.DataFrame(data=group[column_names], columns=column_names)

            tmp.index = [name]*tmp.shape[0]
            
            features[feature].append(tmp.iloc[0])

            features_raw[feature].append(tmp.iloc[0])

        else:    
            tmp = pd.DataFrame(group[feature]).reset_index(drop=True).T
        
            tmp.index = [name]
        
            t_f = np.linspace(0, 99, 100)
        
            t_o = np.linspace(0, 99, tmp.shape[1])
        
            interpolated_df = pd.DataFrame(np.interp(t_f, t_o, tmp.values[0])).T
        
            interpolated_df.index = [name]
            
            features[feature].append(interpolated_df)

            features_raw[feature].append(tmp)

    features[feature] = pd.concat(features[feature])

    features_raw[feature] = pd.concat(features_raw[feature])

The above needs a bit of explanation. The value of 100 was used to interpolate each sequence_id into a standardized dataset. Also, each IMU-based feature is appended to a dictionary. The variables features_raw and features are before and after data cleaning.

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))

plt.title(f"Accelerometer X Channel and Its First Derivative")

plt.xlim(0,100)

plt.xlabel("Counts")

plt.plot(features['acc_x'].iloc[0], label='acc_x', linewidth=0.5)

plt.plot(features['acc_x_1st_deriv'].iloc[0], label='acc_x 1st derivative', linewidth=2, color='red')

plt.legend(loc='lower left')

plt.show()

(feature engineering)The above plot is an example of the first derived feature, the first derivative of the IMU measurements. The business value of this engineered feature, as most engineered features in the space of inertial measurement and control, would be the potentital raising of accuracy, particularly if machine learning is used to stabilize or optimize control algorithms. A specific example could be in better phone location algorithms.

In [24]:
features['accel_magnitude'] = np.sqrt(np.power(features['acc_x'], 2) + np.power(features['acc_y'], 2) + np.power(features['acc_z'], 2))

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))

plt.title(f"Accelerometer Measurements and Calculated Magnitude")

plt.xlim(0,100)

plt.xlabel("Counts")

plt.plot(features['acc_x'].iloc[0], label='acc_x', linewidth=0.5)
plt.plot(features['acc_y'].iloc[0], label='acc_y', linewidth=0.5)
plt.plot(features['acc_z'].iloc[0], label='acc_z', linewidth=0.5)

plt.plot(features['accel_magnitude'].iloc[0], linewidth=2, label='magnitude')

plt.legend(loc='lower left')

plt.show()

(feature engineering)The magnitude of the acceleration measurement can be calculated with the following formula:

magnitude = sqrt( x^2 + y^2 + z^2 )

The business use of the acceleration magnitude is an aggregation of all of the acceleration channels, allowing for a measurement that is less complex than having to look at all three at the same time.
